<subSubSection pageId="1" pageNumber="128" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,151,935]" pageId="1" pageNumber="128">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,321,226,251]" pageId="1" pageNumber="128">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Carapace subrhombus, globular, naked, slightly longer than broad; surface finely granulate; regions well defined, separated by grooves; front slightly bilobed; 
<number box="[804,818,263,287]" pageId="1" pageNumber="128" value="3.0">3</number>
tubercles on gastro-cardiac region; numerous tubercles on branchial region, arranged circle; hepatic, branchial, intestinal regions prominently swollen; middle of anterolateral margin present a small tubercle; posterior margin bilobed.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,151,935]" pageId="1" pageNumber="128">Eyes small; antennule large, folded in fossa; antennular flagella very small. Third maxilliped finely granulate; exopod slightly shorter than endopod; merus of endopod curved, subtriangular, shorter than ischium. Chelipeds subequal, stout, finely granulate; chelipeds merus trigonal; carpus, palm rounded, swollen; fingers upcurved, as long as palm. Pereiopods slender, short, finely granulate except for dactylus; dactylus tomentose.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,151,935]" pageId="1" pageNumber="128">
Male abdominal somites 
<number box="[502,539,514,539]" pageId="1" pageNumber="128" value="4.5" valueMax="6.0" valueMin="3.0">3-6</number>
fused. G 
<number box="[658,668,515,539]" pageId="1" pageNumber="128" value="1.0">1</number>
slender, margin with few setae, distal part slightly curving, tip relatively broad, with small inner terminal pore. G 
<number box="[730,744,551,575]" pageId="1" pageNumber="128" value="2.0">2</number>
much shorten than G 
<number box="[999,1010,551,575]" pageId="1" pageNumber="128" value="1.0">1</number>
, slender, flat, flexible, swollen in the middle. (
<figureCitation box="[251,319,586,611]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="2.[151,250,1631,1653]" captionTargetBox="[152,1436,240,1630]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[151,1436,193,1718]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE 2. Ebalia nudipes Sakai, 1963 (male, 11.8 × 12.1 mm, ZRC 2015.277): A – B, two side of left G 1; C, dorsal view of" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/245059/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="128">
Fig. 
<number box="[303,319,587,611]" pageId="1" pageNumber="128" value="2.0">2</number>
</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="1" pageNumber="128" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,151,935]" pageId="1" pageNumber="128">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,315,622,647]" pageId="1" pageNumber="128">Remarks.</emphasis>
The species is known from two specimens collected in Tosa Bay and Irozaka, 
<collectingCountry box="[1206,1270,624,647]" name="Japan" pageId="1" pageNumber="128">Japan</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Yokoya" box="[1285,1436,622,647]" pageId="1" pageNumber="128" refString="Yokoya, Y. (1933) On the distribution of decapod crustaceans inhabiting the continental shelf around Japan, chiefly based upon the materials collected by S. S. Soyo-Maru, during the year 1923 - 1930. Journal of the College of Agriculture, 12 (1), 1 - 226." type="journal article" year="1933">
Yokoya 
<number box="[1380,1436,623,647]" pageId="1" pageNumber="128" value="1933.0">1933</number>
</bibRefCitation>
[as 
<taxonomicName box="[195,311,658,683]" class="Malacostraca" family="Leucosiidae" genus="Ebalia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="1" pageNumber="128" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="jordani">
<emphasis box="[195,311,658,683]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="128">E. jordani</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
]; 
<bibRefCitation author="Sakai" box="[340,473,658,683]" pageId="1" pageNumber="128" refString="Sakai, T. (1963) Description of two new genera and fourteen new species of Japanese crabs from the collection of His Majesty the Emperor of Japan. Crustaceana, 5 (3), 213 - 233. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.1163 / 156854063 X 00147" type="journal article" year="1963">Sakai 1963</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Sakai" box="[488,548,658,683]" pageId="1" pageNumber="128" refString="Sakai, T. (1976) Crabs of Japan and the Adjacent Seas. Kodansha Ltd, Tokyo, 773 pp., 251 pls." type="book" year="1976">1976</bibRefCitation>
). It differs from 
<taxonomicName authority="Rathbun, 1906" authorityName="Rathbun" authorityYear="1906" box="[750,1050,658,683]" class="Malacostraca" family="Leucosiidae" genus="Ebalia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="1" pageNumber="128" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="jordani">
<emphasis box="[750,866,658,683]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="128">E. jordani</emphasis>
Rathbun, 
<number box="[991,1050,658,683]" pageId="1" pageNumber="128" value="1906.0">1906</number>
</taxonomicName>
, collected in Hawaii, in its nude carapace, placement of tubercles on dorsal surface of carapace, and its barely bilobed frontal margin. The characters of the present specimen agree very well with the detailed description and figures by 
<bibRefCitation author="Sakai" box="[1221,1359,730,755]" pageId="1" pageNumber="128" refString="Sakai, T. (1963) Description of two new genera and fourteen new species of Japanese crabs from the collection of His Majesty the Emperor of Japan. Crustaceana, 5 (3), 213 - 233. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.1163 / 156854063 X 00147" type="journal article" year="1963">Sakai (1963</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Sakai" box="[1371,1428,730,755]" pageId="1" pageNumber="128" refString="Sakai, T. (1976) Crabs of Japan and the Adjacent Seas. Kodansha Ltd, Tokyo, 773 pp., 251 pls." type="book" year="1976">1976</bibRefCitation>
) and we have no doubt they are conspecific. 
<bibRefCitation author="Sakai" box="[664,870,766,791]" pageId="1" pageNumber="128" refString="Sakai, T. (1963) Description of two new genera and fourteen new species of Japanese crabs from the collection of His Majesty the Emperor of Japan. Crustaceana, 5 (3), 213 - 233. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.1163 / 156854063 X 00147" type="journal article" year="1963">
Sakai (
<number box="[745,806,766,791]" pageId="1" pageNumber="128" value="1963.0">1963</number>
: 
<number box="[819,862,766,791]" pageId="1" pageNumber="128" value="216.0">216</number>
)
</bibRefCitation>
observed that “the first male pleopod is the best character for distinguishing the two species, the tip being thin and rather broad”. G 
<number box="[1111,1121,803,827]" pageId="1" pageNumber="128" value="1.0">1</number>
is figured here for the first time (
<figureCitation box="[216,285,838,863]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="2.[151,250,1631,1653]" captionTargetBox="[152,1436,240,1630]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[151,1436,193,1718]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE 2. Ebalia nudipes Sakai, 1963 (male, 11.8 × 12.1 mm, ZRC 2015.277): A – B, two side of left G 1; C, dorsal view of" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/245059/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="128">
Fig. 
<number box="[268,285,839,863]" pageId="1" pageNumber="128" value="2.0">2</number>
</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,151,935]" pageId="1" pageNumber="128">
The present record was obtained from deeper water (
<quantity box="[804,936,875,899]" metricMagnitude="2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.25" metricValueMax="2.28" metricValueMin="2.2199999999999998" pageId="1" pageNumber="128" unit="m" value="225.0" valueMax="228.0" valueMin="222.0">222–228 m</quantity>
